 or sometimes later, we would have - fish, potatoes, mostly fish, not so much of the meat. Mm hm. Because fishing was - the fish was plentiful here in abundance, all kinds of fish, and - milk, granny - granny had two cows, and we used to get a supply of m
i
lk daily from granny, potatoes and milk and fish and then a cup of tea after. Oh we were well fed dear, we never knew what hunger was, especially father being away at the time. Butter was - was cheap in them days. And my father was going - sailing - the s
even seas for four pound a month. Until he got - up as a lamp}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033309\charrsid2102334  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
trimmer and he got a five shilling rise then. And my mother was working for two pound a months, that's half pay he was sending my mother. Oh the half pay he was allowed to send you know, the othe
r half pay was to be kept, they had the two pounds to be kept until he was paid off. But everything was so cheap. A loaf of bread was only - a quarter loaf we - we used to call it, two loaves together, sixpence. Two pounds of sugar sixpence. Sure. And but
ter - an pound of butter a shilling. Cheese would be about nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15033309\charrsid2102334  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
pence the pound. Oh gracious dear - that's how - my mother was able to keep the - family going, herself and six children.
