orm Com. She was from Com. Now she said, you'll bury me where I will ever be facing the Iland of Coll. Well then - that very furthest away point, called Carrackry, you'll see it from here darling. Do you see that point - rock - furthest away, the big one,
 
the big big island is Muldurnock Island, but this dark - black point here again, well that's Onesing, it's Unessia, something like Welsh you know in Gaelic, Unessia, and do you know dear, to put her - to bury her the way - you know, like this you know - y
o
u know she could never see Coll and therefore - her coffin was standing - mind, you know. Upright, that's the word, upright. Upright. And there's a kepple, a something like a - a ruined plinth, a ru - based round her, round her grave, a shrine round her g
r
ave, built stone and lime and all that. But not to where - she could face Coll. That's it now there, on - down there. Uh huh. Unessia. It's a - it's - it's a point you know and you know you get that to point on - on - low tide, low tide only. Just, you kn
o
w, a point of an island out from the - from Carrickry Bay, but - it's a - it's - it's so - it's - it's dry, the sound is dry when the tide is low, cattle and all and everybody can get back and forth over and that. But one strange thing about it. Well then
 
- never - did the cattle - spent the night there, when the dusk would come they would make for the - for the - the mainland as it were. And if the tide - if it happened to - at the - that it - that it was - that they tide came in, they would swim, rather 
than to spend the night on that small point of an island. For whatever, you know, is the cause.
