\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Chrissie is the oldest girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Chrissie, yes, the one that was married down in Yarmouth and she - she died in childbirth. When - there would be - there's two years between me and Chrissie. Granny - always the grannies - granny used to leave - granny Campbell, my granny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Do you remember granny well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Do I not, oh lord did I not - stay with granny for - in the schooldays, slept with granny while her sons - them that wasn't married, there was three in - married at the time - and they used to go to the fishing, to 
the lochs and - I used to sleep with granny. Uh huh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Was she nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
She was near - and I can - yes, her husband was - was - living, Anthony Campbell he was, but he - he died first though. He died - he died - he would be about - near seventy or 
so. But she lived longer than that. And she went to live - with her daughter Mary, her youngest daughter Mary, when my mother came over here. Well - while my mother was, for we were in Kentangval, we used to be - with granny so often, bringing - bringing 
t
he water from the well and taking in the coal or peat or whatever it - tidying up the floor and sleeping with granny and singing songs, the school songs for granny and she was very musical, was a musical little lady, yes, she was. Mm hm. The same granny a
s Thomson has got, Campbell over there. Yes, he's my first cousin, my mother and his father, brother and sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 His father was the leader of the raid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 He was, Duncan Campbell, the leader of the Vatersay raiders, that is right dear, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did your father take a big part in that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Oh no, not at first at all because he was away at sea. It was her you know that my mother that - that went in for this and put my father's name in, so that father would give up the sea complete you know. This was
 the only way that she would like father to give up the sea, thinking that - that through a small croft here you know would be sufficient for to - for a livelihood to bring up the family, but not at all, it was not - it didn't work, but - she was broken-h
e
arted to my father being away in the wintertime you know, with the - the wild raging seas in the wintertime and I remember very well when my father would come in from the voyages, from Buenos Aires and from all them places, her eye would always - it would
 be a telegraph, no phones in them days but the wire'd come in - arrived, all well, Michael. That was just - all the message. Then the letters would come. Mm hm. To ease her mind that - that she would know that father was - safe, mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 It must have been very worrying for her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Very worrying, that's really what made her - come over here, take the croft.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Can you remember if the younger children in the family did anything to help the older children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Well dear - Flora, was just a - Mrs Bro
wn here - I don't know really whether she was - been a year - two or three years in Castlebay, but she got - went to school at five, six, seven, eight, then she attended the school in the farm house there, 'til they - 'til - 'til the school was built, and
 - well they couldn't - do much dear, they was too young. Not much dear, they couldn't do much no. Was mostly for my - Chrissie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 You did most of the looking after of children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes. Yes. Oh yes, dear. Yes. Because my mother - left in my care - and
 never - to let any one of them go here nor there nor anywhere. Some - relations would be wanting them you know, seeing father would be at sea and that my mother - but no, no, no, no, she - supposing perhaps I would be going on my knees to pick the whelks
 for them, supposing I had nothing else - that one would be - go outside the door. Not at all dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you ever eat whelks then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 We did. We did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you boil them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes, boiled them first of course and then take them out with a pin lik
e this. I've seen them sold in Glasgow and in them places in the windows you know. Once a year they send them to Billingsgate from here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 What about seabirds and their eggs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh well the - father was a great hunter. When he would be home in the su
mmer time and the few weeks of autumn, he used to shoot seabirds. Cormorants they called them. They was lovely - something - did you ever take venison, like venison. No fat whatever, no fat whatever, but beautiful and - and dark and what else was - rabbit
, but we was really - was not very keen on rabbits at all. Not very keen on rabbits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 How did you cook the cormorants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Skin them. Some in the olden days they used to pluck them, and - what do you call them again - singe them, and - boil them. But 
after that - getting more advanced and more modern they were skinned. Auite nice and beautiful. Mm. Uh huh. Cleaned and cooked beautiful, oh they're real - delicious. Delicious, just delicious. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Do you know how old your father was when you were born?
