\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 When could you leave the table, did you have to say your grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh, we would have to say the grace and not worry. To sit down there now, 'til we would
 all be finished and say the grace at the table, and then we would get up, help mother clear the table and we'd wash our hands. And - tidy up the table and let mother it - tidy up the table and - if there were, you know, fish - plates - more plates with f
ish on it is - sticky. Away with the plates, hot water in the pot and - wash up the dishes and help mother. Mm hm. That's right
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did your brothers do that too, the washing up of the dishes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No, just the girls only. No dear. But they used to help w
ith carrying water. Mm hm. And go down - go down to meet the boat for fish. See if their father wasn't a fisherman. Mm hm. Go down to meet the boats the boys used to meet them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Would the boys buy some fish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Buy - buy - two or three of the neigh
bours 'cos - it was the custom, all the - the neighbours were needing fish. Mm hm. The small cods - and - what else now, ling, small ling, yes, but the bigger ones were sold dear to the fish merchants, and cured. There was a big curer over in the Island o
f
 Oronsay This station is still there to the same - and the rooms of - of - of - of the house where he used to cure the fish, and counted peats too where he used to cure it until it would be cured for so many days and then lifted up and - to be dried. Well
 in them days the farmers on the mainland were mostly using fish - for their staff and for their farm boys and - mm hm. Mm hm. To farm servants you see, mm hm. So salt fish was in great demand in them days nearer the mainland. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did your family have its own boat at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
No dear, we had no - we were depending on my - my - uncles, my mother's brothers. My grandpa - parent - my grandparents and them at the time, they had the Agnes Brown, they had the Royal Tar, and - grandfather God rest his soul,
 he had a smack, a fishing smack, with - two - two - masts and - and a windjammer. Mm hm. Well when he grew old and the smack went out of action, his sons bought it - the Agnes Brown and - from the east of course they bought and then they bought the Royal
 Tar \{BLANK\} And - of course we used - mother used to get a share of fish or meat, of everything you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 From them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh yes, dear, from granny, oh yes, yes, from granny. Oh yes, yes, they were a clan big family you know. So was - Donald Campbell
 Thomson there - they were the same. Pretty the same as what we were. Because Duncan, his father was - my uncle. He was a laird to his family. They were getting their share.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did your mother ever make any jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Jam - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Or pickles or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No, I - dear, no. No, she never did used to make any jam. No, we weren't up fruity you know. Not at all, no}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 no. It was much of a luxury, too much you know, but not a - but I'll tell you we had sugar and treacle. Not much of the jam at all. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 There isn't a lot of fruit to make it from is there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No, there isn't any anywhere, nothing in Barra, no, nothing in Barra.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did she make anything like beer or wine ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No indeed, the wine - never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Or beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No. Oh never. But I'll tell you what she used to - gruel. Aye. You know, to make gruel, fine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Was a medicine was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Not at all dear. When - when the children would be - first it was the first stage, when the - when they would get - would get up - to four or fi
ve weeks mother would give the - make gruel for them. And that was oatmeal steeped in a big bowl, first of all, cold water, in case it would lump, and then boiling water, and then she would squeeze it, you know, squeeze it - 'til the - all the good would 
c
ome out of it, it would be just as white like milk. She would put it in a saucepan, bring it to the boil, a wee tip of - of - of salt and sugar in. It was like a puree, made a cream, not pudding. But not of the yellowish colour of the cream, however, a li
t
tle cornflower put in, but you no - not so constipated as cornflower. Nice and pure and healthy for the children. And that's what we used to make for the infants. And another thing there wasn't baby powder going them days. It was - linen ash, now, come al
ong, what that is, what is that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Linen burnt and the ash of the linen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Linen ash, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 They burnt linen did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes, they used to bring out the hot red peats, you know, the peats - take out - pull out and - put a - a cloth of linen o
n the - on it, and oh watch that it would not burn do you know, just brownish it would go to an ash, and that was used - instead of baby powder. For, you know, under here and under the arms of the bathing and down here. Yes. Linen ash they call it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Was it a brownish colour still?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Brownish colour dear, yes, yes, yes. Mm hm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 You remember you were saying your father went hunting for rabbits and cormorants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did he do that on Barra too, before you came over?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh yes, 'cos in
 Barra - that it - the most of it But not on the old age pension, not at all, not nearly, but was pretty old man, pretty able to - to go out to the islands there to him - two or three or them used to club together and go out to the islands, out there past
 Muldonoch - for for the day's shooting. And they used to shave the cormorants and the sea birds out to their neighbours. Mm hm. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you grow on your croft, you had a croft in Barra too didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Just - no dear, just my grandfather's. Mm hm. My grandfather's. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did your grandfather and grandmother grow vegetables at all, cabbage or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes, cabbage, yes, cabbage and turnips too. And potatoes. Barley. Oats. And small oats. Mm hm. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 And they gave a lot to you, this was your father's parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Yes, yes, they gave a lot - but we weren't fully depending as regards you know potatoes, we - we had such a big family of us, we used to buy - from the farmers away out west, \{BLANK\} and do you know, t
he price of a hundredweight of potatoes in my day go - when I was in school - my mother only used - two and six. Two and six, then it went up to four shillings and then it went up to five shillings. Then that was eight - eight - eight stones of potatoes. 
Cheap. Cheap in them day. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
When you were on Barra, when you came over here, was there ever a shortage of food, did your mother ever have to stint herself, have less so that the children could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 You always had enough to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
No, we - well how could we, when a cargo boat used to come every week from Glasgow, piled with flour bags. Will you see a flour bag today, ten - ten stone bag of flour, not at all. Oatmeal as well. Mm hm. Oatmeal for porridge, and a bag of flou
r, ten stones of flour, it wasn't a hundredweight at all, it used to be a ten stone bag of flour. Was only ten shillings. Ten shillings, now then. Thirteen - ten - a shilling a stone. Oh different - from today. When you see a boatload coming up, the boat 
today, oh no, oh no, not at all. It gets a - a three pound bag in - in the shop and that, well that's it. No, well they do baking, the most of them do their own baking, they do to tell the truth but - the younger generation mostly use loaf bread. Mm hm.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 When you used to go to bed when you were very small did your mother put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Oh yes dear, and get the slashes on - the backsides, oh get to sleep now. How often - how often she would have to go down to the room. Well we would be taken there
 mind you - especially, if there was anybody, a lady - where would you get up to - to the room, oh well then, we're going to get our blessings from -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did she always just use her hand or did she use a rope sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh yes, she used the rope som
etimes. That is if we would be up too late, and she didn't know where we were, you never - was with our - our other pals you know. Oh dear yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you always have to be indoors at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes, yes. Yes dear. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Even when you were grown up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Yes, even when we were grown up and I was at service and I was at the fishing, and I was leaving my auntie, a sister of my mother, she was married up in Glen to a Mr. Macrae. Well I - and my pal, Nancy Maclean, Katie Johnston,
 and - Mary Campbell, we went to Auntie Mary, up - past Castlebay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 At the Glen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Yes, past Castlebay. And coming back - after leaving Auntie Mary at - past Castlebay this - you know where the school - where the - school house, not the old school 
but the new school, what is - secondary is it they call it - coming up the breae we were just going down where the new school is, coming up the brae the schoolmaster was coming. Is our Kate there, she said. Yes, said Nancy. Now she had the doubled rope be
h
ind her back like that. Home you go before I uses this, right home. And I got it across the shoulders, and scolded when I got home. What was I doing at that time of night. Well it wasn't late, it was between - about - well it was near eleven o'clock on a 
summer night do you know. She was very strict.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 How did you feel about that when that happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Well I didn't \{BLANK\} I was a - a teenage and felt it terrible. But it was her duty and she was doing what she -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 She did what she thought was right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Yes, perfectly dear, yes, she - yes, yes. And I'll tell you another thing she used to say to us. Look here, she said - if you - when you go with anybody, she meant the young men, to any lonely place or out of the way place, she says, the devil is
 the right person. That wasn't wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 She warned you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Yes. Mm hm. And I was in Glasgow - oh she was an awful nice lady as we were staying - lodging with, she was a Mrs Clews. And - she was some mother to us and she would advise us, now don't spe
ak to strangers, don't give your smiles to strangers, and - all that. For she said - she - well - one evening she said to us, there was some others, she said, and she was dying, and her daughters were round her bed. And the advice she gave her daughters w
as this. To her eldest, daughter, let no idle lover whisper nonsense in your ear. And do you know there were three or four rhymes and it was so taking, I - I - I forgot it I couldn't keep it, and I would dearly lve to get these rhymes back
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 I wonder who wrote them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
She - she told them to place a stone at her head, and - oh I - it was so nice really, it was so nice. And I remember another one too anyway. A young girl I knew her well, although she was much older than me, oh she was a rare beauty, she
 was Amelia Mckinnon, and she was serving - with the - with the - boss - of Lochboys to the tin. Of course he was in Barra first and she was with him in her younger days and then he took her - she would be getting near twenty to Lochboys Street. She used 
t
o serve at the tables and that. And - Lewis, her, boyfriend Lewis took a great notion to her. Well then, she fell ill in health. And she didn't like to tell him that she was in ill health. And seemingly dear they weren't so far advanced then as what they 
are today, it was the lung - starting. And - she was fully intending to marry the girl, it was the girl \{BLANK\}
 gentle girl she was. And do you know, he wrote to her, it was her cousin, Nancy Mclean, she's not, she's dead now, that told me this, he wrote to
 her and said - when she told him that they were finished you know - our hands is clasped the last forever, perhaps we'll never meet again. I loved you as I could no other, this parting fills my heart with pain. You asked to free me I forgive you, the hap
p
y past I must forget, and though I wander on in sorrow, I hope that you will be happy yet. As through this weary world I wander, my thoughts will always be of you, in memory you will be with me ever, for I loved you better than you knew. And when the frie
nds have all departed, the friend you thought so kind and true, remember when you left heartbroken, who loved you better than you knew. Isn't it touching and sad. Isn't it dear?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 She never told him the reason she broke off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Well - it was when she had to go to hospital, and - she died. Well they weren't so advanced then as what they are today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Are there a lot of changes on Barra do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes, there is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 When you were a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Mm. Ask anything darling, anything at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did your parents play any games with you, like cards or draughts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Or did they not have that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No. No. Oh no, she was too buys working for us and working for others. She used to take some sewing in and some spinning
 for other people and she used to knit stockings and all that. Oh she was too busy. She had no time dear for that at all. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 What about your granny, did she play games or tell stories and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh she used to tell stories, and tunes and so
ngs, oh she was so cheery a musical, granny. Granny Campbell was. Uh huh, yes, oh she was very - when she was a young girl, she said, when - when she was a young girl staying on Grrick, that's where they were staying when they came over from Uist, and the
y
 were McMillans from Uist, her parents were, and she said, when Lady Gordon Cuthbert, she said, came to Barra, as a young bride of John Gordon, there were seven pipers, she said, on the Gerrick pier meeting her, playing - what was it now - but - Lady Gord
on Cathcart's welcome to Barra, and she used to sing the tune - what was it now she used to sing - \{BLANK\}
 She used to play that you know, in her young days when she - and granny, what were you dressed in? Dressed she said, barefooted she said, and - I had a grey petticoat.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 She had been there and seen it had she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Yes, yes. It was a great day for them, a day to remember. Lady Gordon - coming to Barra. Well - when Gordon, when young Gordon died she married Cathcart. She was Lady Gordon Cathcart, sh
e owned the whole island of Barra, and - it was - oh it's not so very far back since - since the chief McLean of Barra - came from America, and - took on Barra and the castle and all, the chiefta}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 nship and all. And the young chiefs coming here - just in autumn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 We went to the castle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 You went in the castle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Have you been there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Never. I've never been. I would dearly like to - see the castle - and it's the - chief is buried in the walk beside that. And gracious, gracious. And she sleeps at the castle alone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Terribly lonely isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh - nothing like to be just as much as we do, just turn and - to have your comfortable and
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Enough but not too much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Mm, but not too much, mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 I was asking you last time if you e
ver want away for a holiday and you told me how in your holiday you had to look after little babies so that people could go to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 During the school holidays I would have to look after children, the younger babies, of the - of my mother's neighbour
s, the neighbours that would - there were three together working, they were working together in a clan well that's how they were working, three and three and three together. Well she would say, Kate will - will relieve you of your home during her summer h
olidays and - well - it's never for us to say whether we liked it or not, so that was that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 How did they get over to Barra, did they go in a boat every day and come back in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh darling, my mother never went to the fishing once we get here. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 But did some of the women?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Uh huh. Yes, in a wee boat. That's right, back - back at the end of the day, that is right. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 When did they get a church here on Vatersay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 There was no church at all, but the priest used 
to come over every third Sunday and have mass in the school house and until that church was erected in \{BALNK\}
 But we used to go over every Sunday, summer and autumn, and fine Sundays during the winter, across the Sound here and across the hill walked. That's right. Mm hm. Two or three boats would go and take all the - old people. Mm hm. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 That church in Barra, did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 In my case dear I did belong to the choir. Every Sunday we had Mass at nine o'clock for the children, w
hile I - my teenage I turn - when I was a teenager I used to got the choir. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 And sing in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Mm. Mm hm. The hymns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Were there any clubs at the church? Or sort of social evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No. No. There had to be a soiree concert in Borve
, in the - at Christmas. New Year and Christmas and New Year. And every now and again - say - between there used to be dances - when the hall was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 erected. First it was the school house, and that couldn't be you know - but seldom, because - the boys and gir
ls would be a dance on Friday night, it wouldn't be convenient every Friday night. So it would be once a month or so, until the hall was - hall was built. For them to call and - they used to have their dances there - and their - caileys and - concerts. Mm
. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did your parents think it was wrong to work or play on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
We were not to work at all, at all, no work on any conditions whatever. But we - we were allowed to play. As regards - ring-a-ring-a-rosie and London Bridge is falli
ng down, and I came to see Georgina George and things, and played the like, uh huh, but no work whatever. Not - on a Sunday, but Mass and Benediction and - mm hm. And prayers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 You told me how hard your mother had to work looking after all of you and 
doing sewing, did she have any kind of recreation, any time when she could enjoy herself not working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Go to see her mother just across the road and then go to see her auntie away at the bridge at Kentangval.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 That was her pleasure was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 T
hat was our - that was all dear and - looking forward for Sunday and - word from father from - Rio de Janeiro or from - some port in Australia, some port in - Spain.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Letters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Juhuh. Oh yes, yes, yes. Mm hm. And word from the other - she used to 
get word of him from the others - the whereabouts of the ship. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did she have any friends she used to go and see, or just the relations you mentioned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Just relations. But - but with outsiders though - that used to keep her busy, as regards 
knitting as I told you and already, knitting, weaving and that sort of thing, she was getting paid for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 She did weaving too did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Well - oh knitting. Mm. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 But she didn't have friends who weren't related to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 She - she had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 dear - the pals she had in them days she had them all along.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 She had her pals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Yes, such as Mrs Campbell. And - Margaret McNeil. And - who else, Peggy McDougall, yes, yes, yes, she used to have - the girls that used to be with her at the fi
shing in her young days, although they were married, they used to keep that up all the time. Pally. Pally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did they go and see each other in their houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes, very often they would see - two or three - of the pals, and - they would have a cup o
f tea and they would talk - talk over their young days when they were fishing - at the fishing at Fraserburgh or Peterhead, Lerwick, and enjoy their talk themselves. Yes. Mm hm. That's right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 If they came round they'd just call in would they, would they just knock and walk in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Not at all, no knock at all in the fashion. That wasn't in the fashion at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Just walk in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Walk in. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 If a person came in would they always be offered something to drink, a cup of tea, or was that not the fashion then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 A cup of tea, always. Yes. Unless they would say - well just after - I've had some, don't bother, or something like that, mm hm, mm hm.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did people ever come in for a meal in those days, for tea or to sit down for a meal, or was that not the fashion at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 They used to come for a meal, them that would come - distant villages. Cutting seaweed. For manure. They would be cutting sea}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 wood, piling, carrying it in creels and piling it in their big box, save it for their winter
 days, until it would be getting kind of - you know, slimey like, that's the best thing for potatoes. Well, seeing that were - from - from - from a distance and she knew them anyway from her younger days and that, she would - call them in for a cup of tea
 and they would be very - I know that, I remember that very well. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Where would they sleep when they came over like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Would they go home at night to sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Well, yes dear, they would walk, it would be only a matter of 
three miles. Not very far, they would walk it. But I'll tell you one thing in my mother's days, well it's still the fashion here too, whatever they get is - if it was meat or if it was a kill - a kill - kill a sheep - or two, in the house, that's customs 
at New Year, or get some - plenty - plenty of fish, they would share it with their neighbours. Share it dear with the neighbours, yes, yes. Well - the - the same here now. Oh it's the same now, uh huh.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did your family ever collect the keep, the seaweed, was it called kelp?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
I was collecting seaweed ever since I came here, when we came here in 1910. Collecting seaweed and putting it in to a heap at the roadside, taking it up in creels on our back. Putting it down at the roadside until it would - ge
t kind of slimey, what - you know what I mean do you, Mm. And that's the best thing for the - for the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Lazy beds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Mm hm. That for the lazy beds. And that was done - a man from the - the Department of Agriculture about eighteen months ago in the
 school house, he was lecturing - fertilizers and all this and that for fertilising for the soil. Well - about six years back I was to - I was at a lecturing - at a meeting, a man from department lecturing too, and this one was lecturing - and - about fer
t
ilizers and - and we could ask any question at all we liked. And, now I said, excuse me, I was here about six years back, I said, and there was a - an official from the department lecturing about fertilizers. And he said that the best fertilizer, the best
 
ever for soil, was the seaweed. But to leave it I say in a heap for so many days and - yes, he said, that is right, that is the best, he said, ever. But it takes too much manpower - labour, you know Mm, that's what he said. That's the best - and so that's
 what they're using here too, the sea}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 wood. Mm hm. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you go fishing when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
No, I did not here in Barra, but up in Lerwick - up in Lerwick we used to go fishing - we - we would get the privilege of to go fishing with them 
if we would bait the line for them, bait the line. And we'd get lovely fishes. We'll have fresh fish tonight say, and - smoked - then we'll smoke them tomorrow and have the smoked fish too, the smoked herring and that. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you ever go to any kind of cinemas or magic lantern shows or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Now - in - well down in - Yarmouth, we used to go to the - to the pictures, and to the - Hippodrome and to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334 Coliseum}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 , and when in Lowestoft too, the next fishing port, when the seasons were there w
e used to go to the pictures. And enjoy it very much. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 But not on Barra?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh no, there wasn't such a thing here, no. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 When you were a child could you play with any children you liked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Any children at all, any at all dear we would.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 There were no distinctions at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
No distinction, two would - two would - two would fall out and them come home and greet. And then the mothers'd say - do you know what she would say? If you would keep to yourself, and if you would behave yourself, now you wouldn't get that. \{BLANK\}
 She wasn't going out to fight for us, not at all. Mm. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you - did she ever say that the boys should hit back if they were hit or did she think they shouldn't hit back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No. No, not that I know of. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 I was asking you about your mother's friends, what about your father, did he have pals that he'd had from childhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh, yes, and now during his holidays - when - when finished with his work. Such as the boating - the boating captain name
d Mr Stuart. He had - he had a boat Mr Stuart had and he was taking my father up - excuse me - and - whenever the next one he would come home, get home and get his tea and back, he was not going empty, he would be going to cailey you know, with the - his 
brother Hector and - his brother Hector, that's the - that's his name}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334  sa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
ke, Hector McLeod of the ferryboat. His mother and - first cousins.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did they have any of the same friends, your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 We got the same friends, yes dear, the same
 friends. He would be - people you were friendly she was friendly with. Oh no difference whatever. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
When you were telling me about when your youngest sister and your youngest sisters were born who helped your mother when she was in bed, did they stay in bed a long time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Ten days. Ten days then. That was dear over in Kentangval, not here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 They were all born in Kentangval?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh, the youngest was - getting out to school, five, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Who looked after the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Granny. Granny, she did, mm hm. Then women of - round about would come in, they would go up to the old - bedroom and - whatever changes she would need you know and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Look after her?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 In Kentangval did you share the house with your granny or did you have a separate house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
No, we had a house of our own. Mm hm. No, granny had a house here with three rooms it was. A wee bedroom and a big room, there was two beds in the big room, and the kitchen. But then she had a lovely out hous
e too, and - that outhouse, my mother got - got - it until her own house was put up, at - in Clemarick there, you know, in the bay, at the head of the bay, Kentangval, and - after my mother's - Mary got it, the daughter. And so did Duncan. And so did Rog 
- Roderick, mm hm. Aunt Mary, Roderick. Oh yes, mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 And then she moved out of the outhouse to a house did she then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh yes, my mother moved out of here when her own house was built. You see, it was the same with - Mary. She moved to Glen, with
 her husband when their own house was - was ready, mm hm. And so did Duncan. So did Roderick. Many, Roderick.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Last time you were telling me about the different social classes and you were saying the working class, there were no distinctions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh 
not at all dear, you wouldn't find - they wouldn't look down on us at all. Not at all, no, no, not at all, there wasn't that snobbery at all then. There was only - there was big class - a few merchants, minister and the priests and the schoolmasters. Mm h
m. Was about - doctor. Doctor. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Who were the people who had the most respect and the most honour do you think in Castlebay at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 The priest and minister. And doctor of course, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 What about the merchants, how did your family feel about them at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Well they were very nice and they were very obliging, oh yes although - just - they were depending on those few people and their money you know, their earnings and - they would have to be you know, they were all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Were you brought up to salute some people and not others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
We would salute our priest, and minister, our schoolmaster and anyone say - that would come - Members of Parliament - and officers and the officials. Oh yes, we weren't to go past our headmaster's without a salute. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did anybody ever curtsey at that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did anyone ever curtsey? Do you know what I mean? Sort of bow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 To a bishop. Yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Not to the ordinary minister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No dear, just salute and bow - bow the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Bow the head?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes, and the - boys do something like this. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 You were telling me there are no distinctions now between the Protestants and the Catholics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Not at all. Them days are gone. Oh no, no, no, nothing whatever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 But in the old days you were saying the better jobs were Protestant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Yes. At the High - at the Highland and Island clearance - either they were sent away whether they liked it - liked it or not, on the boats to - the away - ab
road. And quite a lot of them died on board the boats too. And I was told - that a lot of them died too after landing, that they were even trying to keep themselves alive by eating the grass along the roadside, and that they were dying by the roadside, wi
t
h their mouth green, trying to keep themselves a - alive. That was the landlords at the time. They were cruel you know. Well then - the best Protes - not to go behind bush about it but nothing stands but the truth. The best posts were given to the Protest
ants that were brought to Barra from Skye and - you know, that way round about yes. The fact is I know, oh yes, that is right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 And the people at the Post Office, were they Protestants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 At the Post Office? The Register Office. Eoligarry. \{BLANK\} Yes. And - \{BLANK\} the same. \{BLANK\}
 The doctor the same. And one or two on the Island of Vatersay the same. And man that was running the mails from Castlebay to Barra Head - all Protestant. Well that has worn away dear, that has gone - it had it - they had
 - it it had it's day but - we mustn't be -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Do you remember if a person said of somebody at that time, he is a gentleman or she is a lady, what did they mean at that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Well - above - something above the common, you know, that got a training
, that got a good education, and a good bringing up, of course manners and polite and - all that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 It wasn't to do with having money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No dear, no, that wasn't cou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 ting at all, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 It was the quality of the person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Mm hm. That's it now, quality of person. That was the genuine part of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 That's what - people meant in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 That's really the truth, that's what was meant in them days, mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 There was a policeman in Barra wasn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes, there was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 How did he treat the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Very nice. I'll tell you now how did he treat the people. My grandfather McKinnon was a factor, was McKinnin of Barra. My forebears on the McNeil side - were taken from - what do you - oh Spurra, from Spurra - Is
le of Skye, well McNeil of Barra, to get Protestants in their position you know - this is where he got the money to be his factor. Well - he had a piece of land free over there, Kentangval. And - he came to the point of the day where people were to be sen
t away - off Barra. And - the boats - the ships came to anchor - Castlebay there, for to take them away. But first of all, before they were taken away, their houses were to be - you know - the roofs ripped, taken all the thatch taken off and the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 So the people couldn't inhavit it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Mm hm. Here - the policeman came to my grandfather, first he got the orders and the - land to - from McLeod borough and so did my grandfather the factor. You have to go to Bruerish, to the west end of Barra, and you hav
e to take - to hold - the - the whole - hole - make the holes in the roofs, you know, off the roof and - and the thatch. Now, this - McLeod - he called at my grandfather's house in Kentangval. Are you ready, Finlay, he said, to go. Yes, said my grandfathe
r
, they're all ready. So from Kentangval to they came facing Brairick, they walked down the way without saying a word to each other, not a blessed word did the policeman say to my grandfather not my grandfather said to him until they faced Braivic, going u
p
 Braivic Brae. Finlay, he said, we will understand each other. Yes, says my grandfather, we will understand each other, that will be quite all right. So - when they came to Bruerish, and that's a good few miles from - from - Kentangval and Braivic, the po
liceman, you know he's got a - a - what do you call it - a - a stick - a -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 A truncheon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Mm hm, aye, a bat - bat - baton or something. He did like this to the roof of the house. Took his baton and - like that under the thatch, and weakened the th
atch. Now Finlay, he says, that's old. Now he says, see a weakness, so my word he said, that is holed. And that was all he did. Now, wasn't he good now? He was a good man. Mm hm. Uh huh. Well this man that came from Skye, he married a Barra woman, and - t
hat's the McKinnons up to this day. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 When you were a child, they were no old age pensions then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Not at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Were there many old people who were destitute?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 There was some old people - that was only getting - the - the - the poor - the poor - get the poor, what do you call it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Relief?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
That's - three and six a month or something. - But the most of them - it was the obligations of their children - to support their aged parents in their old age. Wasn't that good dear. That 
was blessed and holy. That was the way now all over the island. And another thing, where the eldest son wouldn't get married, he was getting the other end of the house and the parents in the centre until he would be able to get a - to make a - a place of 
his own. And his duty and obligations to do everything they could to the - to their parents That's it. Now that - that's the truth and that's what they used to do here when there was no pensions for them. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you ever hear on Barra if a person d
id something thast other people disapproved of, did they ever make a noise outside their house with a lot of tin cans and things like they used to do in England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Not at all dear, but I will tell you what they used to do you see. They would do nothing at all. Out of the way \{BALNK\}
 It would be cursed into the - the family from generation to generation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 If somebody had done a bad thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Mm. Now, I'll give you an instance here \{BLANK\} I'll give an instance here. Over in Kentangval before we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334 came here, there was a woman, I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7808721\charrsid2102334 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
bella Macrae, in her young days she was working down with farms - farms at London, South of Scotland, near the borders, and she came home with a baby child, a boy. From that woman's time - right down to twenty-five years befo
re the - a child - of the same kind was born. Twenty-five years between - such a case.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 So rare was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 When that woman came back, how did people treat her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh, she was more to be pitied do you see, used to help her kind and her own folk, and her own people used to help her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did she ever marry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
No, she never did. But her son - Alexander Kennedy, he did marry. But - I was told in his young days that the other - school - friends and - his pals used to cast a
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Can you tell me what you did when you first left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
When I first left school - I was a home help with a lady, a retired school teacher, and - she was bad through loss of memory, and it was her husband that - that was - it was her husband that my fa
ther was working with - at - on the boating. On the boat dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Mr Stuart?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Mr Stuart, back and forth from the cargo boats, and - he asked my other, their only daughter Mary Ann died and he asked my mother would he let me - for the summer season -
 to be a companion with - you know, because she - he didn't see - she had - her memory was so bad that she wasn't able to know whether she had taken her breakfast, she would forget to take her breakfast and she would neglect herself, you know, and - she w
ould put on her clothes all right, and her shoes, but as regards the fire, it was the fire and coal, it was dangerous and risky, she was getting childish you know. Well that was my very first job and - eight shillings a month. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you go in the morning and come back in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Oh I used to stay dear in the house, I used to stay with the lady, stay, but I had a room of my own. A room of my own, yes. The room that their own daughter had, I used that one. They were very very very nice to me
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did they treat you like one of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 One of the family. One of the family. With them at breakfast and the dinner and tea and everything. Just like one of their own family. Mm.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh yes, I did. I cooked - but wond
er - wonders of the wonder - wonders of the wonder, she used to do the baking, when I would put the flour in the bowl for her and soda, cream of tartar, she would work - and I would do the - yes. And that's the honest truth to be with anybody - in her hou
se that she knew the day she was going to die. And she would say, they'll soon be stretching in my grave. And the last time \{BLANK\}
 oh how beautiful everything is. Oh how lovely the sea, the skies, the seas. The islands, she would say, everything's so beautiful. To help me when I - be crossing the Jordan, I'm just near the end of the road so - that's it. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 You were brought up a good Christian and God-fearing. She had a good mother with her at the end?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Well - yes
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did the brothers come in time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh they were younger dear, they were younger than her And they were so fond of each other too. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 So you did some baking for her you were saying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh yes, yes, yes. Well I used to - fry fish and cook the fish and potatoes and meat
 and all that. Do the housework and the scrubbing. All that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 How often did she let you go home to your own home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh, I could quick run down home, go home every afternoon if I cared to, if I wished to, anyway I would have to collect the milk. I -
 with the McKinnon's. Down at Kentangval Loch there, and - he was back early then I would get to run home, home to - see my mother and the rest of the children, oh and - anything at all that he would get you know, as regards - now when the work was over a
n
d my father being at home, if any boats used to come into the pier, as very often they did with fresh fish and that, Mr Stuart would say, now - take your run down home, take that home, that fresh fish - for you mother to cook for the children. Oh they was
 nice, they was great really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you have a whole day off ever when you could go home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No. No. Sunday. Sunday, I would have the half day at Sunday, that's right
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did she expect you to be home at a certain fixed time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No dear, no. No, 
just I was like one of the family, I would be home anyway you know. Early home anyway say about ten o'clock and that. Uh huh. During the summer time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did they have prayers at night there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes, dear, they had prayers. And the minister, there was 
- they were Protestant. The minister used to come occasionally and say a special prayer and blessing the house. Mm hm. And I would be there too and all with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 You didn't mind that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Not at all, not at all dear, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 In your own home had you had prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
Well - it was a standing just - the - the rosary, every evening the rosary. Yes. Well our own prayers in the morning. In the morning, our prayers, whenever we would get up, get dressed and say their prayers. Then get a meal, 
bless yourself and say the grace before meals and say the grace after. We gave the thanks to Almighty God. That's it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 How long did you stay there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 I was with them for a year. I was with her for a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Why did you leave then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
