 That's right. Well I knew - I was - but during the war there was no fishing, 14 - 1914 war. I went into - one of the factories. Houston, in Glasgow. It was a founder factory, and we had to wear respirators. You know, shell fill factory, and -
 we had to take the shells - four shells on each trolley, away with them to the press room, and they were going under the press, and that was a round steel thing, a round plate from the roof of the press room, with four steel spires, you know, and these f
o
ur spires were going one into each shell, and there - there was a gril in the press room but we - we would usually have to go out. It was very risky you know, whenever the powder was - the steels going in and and the pressure going on, heated up you know,
 it was liable to explode. There was an explosion, but it was a night duty, I wasn't on night duty at that time at all, you would have to be a fortnight on day duty and a fortnight on night duty. Mm hm.
