e was proclaimed. Oh my dear. Twelve o'clock we were on the night shift and we came home - at - between five and six o'clock in the morning and went to bed. Oh at midday the bells of Glasgow rang. The horns and hooters going to Paisley Road. Peace proclai
med, oh and jumped out and got something on \{BLANK\}
 And we went to Paisley Road. My goodness, if you would hear all the cries of some of the - the women - that wasn't expecting their own to come back but lost their - sons you know, it was hard indeed for a 
lot - when the day that peace was proclaimed, oh my dear, if you would hear the - the strings are in my ears. Oh it was really hard, it was a joy to us and to everybody that didn't lost a - you know, a brother or a father or - but to them that did lost - 
their - lose their brothers and pair - father - it was very hard.
