\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Can you tell me something about the clothes in those days, were all the clothes for the family made at home in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 My mother took in making frocks and - and things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 She made your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Of course she did, and sewing with the hand. Hand sewing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 And knitting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No machine, no - the first machines
 I'm sure I would be ten years old before I saw a sewing machine. Mm hm. And I - I got - a treadle - tailor's sewing machine myself. Yes, and it was the first - machine that I put my foot on. And I learned gradually, of course my brother - give me kind of
 an idea and I was going slowly and slowly, as if you were afraid of a thing, I think it's the - it's the - I think it's the wisest thing to venture everything like that. To go as if you were afraid of it, 'til you will get - into the way. Yes. Mm hm.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
When you were a child can you tell me something about the mealtimes in those days, what did parents say about behaviour at mealtimes in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh yes - the table - was just lifted over like - say there was a bench, it was father who used to lift
 the table over, then get our chairs and stools you know, because - a small family was a family of five in them days. Seven and so on and ten was in some families. And - well they always had dinner, kind of at dinner time, like potatoes and they would hav
e
 fish along with it, or - or - meat. The meat. But not - not always you know, but at Christmas they could - afford at all they would have - meat and - some used to kill - cows and so on or - you know, because - the - the sales were so far away like. In Ob
a
n. And - you couldn't - dispose of animals in them days like - the sales were not in Barra. You understand? And they were using up most of their own food was like that you understand? Uh huh. They used to have a lot of potatoes, and - well I didn't see - 
t
he - the meal grinded at all, but I know it was in Mingulay, I heard, you know that they had the grinding stones for it, but I remember - barley meal, very dark - I - I remember a scone - once being in the house of barley meal, that was given by some frie
nds. But it was oatcakes and flour - Indian mixed with flour, it was lovely too, and butters. It was lovely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did your mother bake quite a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh - yes, she had to bake. Very very seldom we - got loaves. I remember - I'm sure it was one hamper of
 bread that the merchants of Barra used to get each. And - I suppose that would be in the fishing season. And - not long after that - one family would need to get a hamper. You understand? The way - you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 So people had to bake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Yes. My first memory - hardly any boats came to Barra. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 In the morning, did you have breakfast all seated together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Of course. That is, if the father was not going to fishing, or to boating, in the summer, you know, my father when he was at home - you k
now - if he would come home at all it would be the summertime and he was boating, this boating was - carrying empties from - you know - a big boat full of empty barrels, into the curing stations, and the - she would take a cargo of salt herring going away
 then. You understand? When they would empty the - that big vessel. The cargo boat, yes. And he - he was never - idle. He was never idle while we were in Kentangval, well he was fishing in Coalis when he was home at summer or t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6434286\charrsid2102334 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 tally retired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 When he was at home did he do anything in the house to help at all, housework or cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
No, not cooking. Well, if there were herring to be done they would do it, if there was anything about - well they would help to go out with and - the \{BLANK\} they were n
ever idle. And of course he worked the boats, tarring them, painting them, out fishing. He used to go even alone to Papa Sound and these places. Oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 But he didn't do any domestic work in the house at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Oh - no, but he could do it, if it was - if he was left to do it he would do it. He was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Can you ever remember him doing any cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No, not while I was in the house because I could do it myself you see. But - he had a very very good idea - because - before we came from 
Lerwick one year he had - he had a carpenter and a joiner here - theirselves, and - he could make his own scones, put them in a frying pan and - a cover on top of that like a - an enamel plate, he lifted that up a wee bit from the fire. The holidays, the 
school holidays. I remember \{BLANK\}
 the lady - you know, she was - she was staying on the island and they called her - they called her - the doctor's wife, he was really the doctor, and she had a lot of family. She had seven sons at least, and three daughte
rs. Anyway, she said to me this day - we'll give you the holidays now, the schoolmaster, Mr Campbell, and when he came home after the holidays, they said, he gave us the play - play, you know the play, but you never gave us the holidays. He thought it was
 something you - you was going to have then. You understand? Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 And you'd never heard of a birthday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
I never had a birthday, it was in school, Mr Campbell. And another thing, I never hung my stocking up. I heard about - when I was in Baptist s
chool, I would be about twelve then, and - anyway, I hanged up my stocking, because I heard about it, you see. And my brothers put a wee bag o sand inside my stocking, that was the one that got mostly in Barra, and after that I knew there was no Santa Cla
us. That it was the parents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 I would be about twelve. Twelve. Never hung my stocking. Unless I would hang it now
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4786465 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 Did you have a Sunday school treat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10050444 KG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 No, we had just a school treat. A school treat. I was only at o
ne school treat and I - and I - and that was only Castlebay. I would attend the fishing over on the other side - to bring up the family. I had four of a family.
