BLANK\} in a wholesale dairy in Glasgow where you used to supply the oth
er dairies in - in Glasgow, north side and south side - well I was at the machines you know. Such as the - what do you call it again, sterilizing, with the - thermometer coming to sixty degrees and not higher, then the cooling - process would be going and
 the milk churns, with sixty pounds, sixty - sixty gallons of cream and the electr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6434286\charrsid2102334 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4289636\charrsid2102334 
c churn going, you know, press the button and the - wheel going around or something like that. Pressing the button and cleaning the button and - says the boss to me - the fir
st day, do you know, he says, how to wash - how to - clean butter? Now he says. I think I do, I said. The way we used to do at home. He said, now, says he, is this for butter? No, I says, not, that's not - the big tub, well of course the tub wasn't round 
w
hen I was lifting it, and the big tub was on, then the house of cold water, when the tub would flow over it would go down through the drains, the - you know the holes for the rain to go, and washing the butter as you are washing wool, you know, let the - 
e
very drop of milk that you could clear out of it. And two or three tubs full of that water and washing the butter and then printing it. And going up to the diary, just at - front, dairy, with the half pound print paper. Butter to be sold after the making.
 Mm hm. Oh well, that wasn't very well, but I used to be up at this time in the morning. Every morning in life they were - were down, he would be down then and the shutters off and then I would have to make toast and cup of tea for him and then get going.

